defaultQ35 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Could I first of all say to the witnesses how grateful we are for you coming back, given the unexpected circumstances of last week
default?
default  
defaultParliament seems to be very busy at the moment
default.  
defaultWe also have a very contentious issue on the floor of the house
default.  
defaultThere may be some votes and there are procedural questions that we also will have to manoeuvre between
default.  
defaultI am going to start with the first question, to pick up where we left off, and this is addressed to all of you
default.  
defaultIn the case of 
defaultTest-
defaultAchats
default, did the applications of Articles 21 and 32 of the Charter, in your view, lead to an extension of the scope of EU law, given that an explicit derogation in the Directive was 
defaultdisapplied
default by the court
default?  
default&#xa0;
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default I do not think it did, because the Directive itself quite clearly sets out a principle of non-discrimination between the sexes in Article 5(1)
default.  
defaultThe Directive sets out a very clear principle of sex equality
default.  
defaultOne of the reasons why the court annulled Article 2 was because they found there was a lack of coherence in a Directive that sets out quite clearly the requirement for non-discrimination but then goes on to insert an exemption clause, which seems to have an almost unlimited applicability
default.  
defaultThe fact that the Directive made references to the Charter in its preamble strengthens that point, because it showed the urge of the European institutions to respect the principle of equal treatment
default.  
defaultAn important factor here was a poorly drafted instrument that suffered from a fatal inconsistency
default.  
defaultProfessor Craig:default I agree with what my colleague said
default.  
defaultI do not think the result would have been any different whatsoever before the Charter from what it would have been after the Charter
default.  
defaultIn a sense, I do not believe that the Charter was instrumental in reaching a different conclusion from what otherwise would have been reached
default.  
defaultPrior to the Charter, the ECJ would have applied general principles of law and they would have reached exactly the same conclusion
default.  
defaultI do not, therefore, believe in that sense that the Charter has led to a different result from that which would have otherwise been reached
default.  
defaultDavid Anderson:default I agree with both my colleagues
default.  
defaultI do not think I can usefully add anything
default.  
defaultMartin Howe:default I firmly disagree with all of my colleagues on this point
default.  
defaultFirst of all, I do not think that internal inconsistency can be a sufficient basis of itself for knocking out derogation
default.  
defaultBy definition, derogation may well be inconsistent with the general scheme laid down in the Directive in that 
defaultit makes a carve
default-
defaultout
default from its general provisions
default.  
defaultI cannot see that itself, by any credible intellectual path, lead to the derogation being invalidated
default.  
defaultSecondly, I acknowledge that there was, before the Charter was given legal effect, the doctrine of principles of law common to the member states
default.  
defaultI do not agree that in the absence of the Charter that would have been a credible or sufficient basis for the European court to knock out the derogation, since if you look at the time of the adoption of the Directive at the laws of the various member states, many member states had systems where differential premiums could be charged on insurance between genders on a statistical basis
default.  
defaultIt seems to me to say that there is a credible basis in that there is a sort of European consensus that this must be treated as a form of sex discrimination would be wrong and probably unsustainable
default.  
defaultI do think that this is an instance where the Charter has resulted in a significant shifting of the goal posts
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ36 default&#xa0; 
defaultJacob Rees-Mogg: Is the reasoning of the Court of Justice in 
defaultFransson
default consistent 
default  
defaultwith Article 51(1) of the Charter?
default&#xa0;
defaultMartin Howe:default The court would argue that it is consistent with it, in that it is an interpretation of it that gives a very wide meaning to when member states are implementing Union law
default.  
defaultThe issue is this: European Union law harmonises the levels of certain taxes, specifically the quantum of VAT
default.  
defaultIt does not seek to harmonise the procedures that member states use for the collection of taxes, which remain a matter for national law
default.  
defaultThe reasoning of the European court in that case was, because some of the taxes that the tax system collects are harmonised, the procedures employed by the tax system become within 
defaultthe scope of the implementation of European Union law
default.  
defaultAgain, this lacks intellectual credibility and it is an example of the court expanding the scope of its jurisdiction, albeit in that case they decided it was not contrary to the Charter
default.  
defaultNonetheless, having rolled the log out with this very wide-ranging interpretation, they are now in a position to apply the Charter over a wider field in future cases
default.  
default 
defaultDavid Anderson:default I do not think the 
defaultFrannson
default case was in any way surprising
default.  
defaultIt is true that Article 51(1) says that the Charter applies to member states only when implementing Union law
default.  
defaultBut it was apparent right from the start, if one read the explanations, that phrase was to be understood as “in the scope of Union law”. In support of that, the explanations cited pre-Charter case law, for example the 
defaultERT
default case, on the scope of the general principle of fundamental rights, which did not only apply when member states were, strictly speaking, implementing, but applied also when they were derogating from or were otherwise within the scope of Union law
default.  
defaultBefore 
defaultFrannson
default, that was the line taken by the High Court in 
defaultZagorski
default and by the Supreme Court in Mr Howe’s Rugby Football Union case that he told us about last week
default.  
defaultTherefore, it seems to me very unsurprising that the 
defaultFrannson
default case came to the result that it did
default.  
defaultAs I mentioned in my written evidence, it is perhaps significant that, although some member states intervened in that case to oppose the reading that the court eventually came up with, the United Kingdom was not among them
default.  
defaultYou may or may not think that was wise, but in any event it does suggest that there was no great opposition to it
default.  
defaultAs Professor Craig says in his supplementary note, the reason why the court ruled as it did in 
defaultFrannson
default was because it took the view Swedish law was being used to implement the obligations flowing from a Directive and, therefore, the Article 51(1) test was satisfied
default.  
defaultHowever, in support of the case that I was putting last week—which is that there is as yet, at any rate, no sign of this court being rights crazed in its approach—I would refer to the conciliatory statement towards the end of the judgment saying that, where the court of a member state is called on to review whether fundamental rights are complied with by a national measure in a situation where the action of the member state is not entirely determined by EU law, the courts remain free to apply national standards of protection, so long as the level of protection provided for by the Charter is not compromised
default.  
defaultThat suggests to me, if one reads the tea leaves, possibly a divided judgment—a judgment in which there was anxious debate about what the result should be
default.  
defaultHowever, in any event, it was a cautious ruling, predicted in advance by the English courts, and it was a very long way from the much more radical idea that one saw suggested by the British Advocate General in the 
defaultRuiz-
defaultZambrano
default case
default.  
defaultProfessor Craig:default I agree with pretty much everything that David Anderson has just said
default.  
defaultI would add three points
default.  
defaultFirstly, I believe that the interpretation of member states implementing EU law in Article 51 to mean member states acting within the scope of EU law was the correct interpretation
default.  
defaultAny other interpretation would have led to formalistic distinctions and, moreover, the explanations had been there for over 10 years, making very clear that is what the EU and member states intended by the Charter
default.  
defaultThat is point one
default.  
defaultPoint two is that I do not believe, in this particular instance, that the application of the idea of member states acting within the scope of EU law was, in any sense, excessive
default.  
defaultI, with respect, differ from the opinion of the German Federal Constitutional Court, which regarded the 
defaultjudgment in this respect as excessive
default.  
defaultThe reason why I disagree is conceded by supplementary evidence and, to go to the heart of it, the point, as far as I can see, is this: the Court of Justice has made it clear in its early case law that the regime of VAT Directives imposes an obligation on member states to take all legislative and administrative measures appropriate for ensuring the collection of all VAT due on their territory
default.  
defaultThat obligation seems to me unexceptional and unarguable
default.  
defaultThe operative or determinative issue, therefore, is not whether the Swedish law in 
defaultAkerberg
default 
defaultFrannson
default was itself enacted to implement the VAT Directive, but whether it was being used to implement the obligations flowing from the Directive, which it clearly was
default.  
defaultThis was not, therefore, a case where someone was trying to tag on to European law through some incidental fact that was not really central to European law
default.  
defaultThe third point is that I would reiterate the point that David Anderson made: I do not think it was a divided court
default.  
defaultMy understanding is that the court very specifically made clear at the end of its judgment that, although this fell within the scope of EU law, the member states would be given some real latitude as to the meaning of fundamental rights as applicable in this case
default.  
defaultTherefore, the national conceptions of fundamental rights would be given all due weight
default.  
defaultFinally, as part of that third point, even if the ECJ does find that the national law is inconsistent with EU 
defaultlaw, that
default does not touch the ability of Sweden to have exactly the same tax enforcement regime in domestic law
default.  
defaultIt merely says that
default you cannot,
default insofar as you are using it to enforce this VAT Directive
default 
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default You have heard very 
defaultfulsome
default answers from Professor Craig and David Anderson, and I do not have anything to add to what they have said
default.  
defaultI agree with both of them
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ37 default&#xa0; 
defaultJacob Rees-Mogg:default What nexus of EU law do you think is required post 
defaultFransson
default to trigger the application of the Charter in a member state
default?  
defaultLooking at VAT in the UK, the government collects over £100 billion a year but only 15% of it is our contribution to the EU
default.  
defaultIs it that a little leaven leavens all the bread
default?  
default&#xa0;
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default It is difficult to put a precise amount on that
default.  
defaultThe Advocate General in that case suggested a need for a more specific connection, but each case is going to turn on its own facts
default.  
defaultWhere you have a national measure that is playing a role in implementing a specific measure of EU law, there is a good case for saying that measure can fall within the scope of EU law
default.  
defaultDavid Anderson:default The relevant factor, at least in the court’s mind, is not what proportion of the revenue finds its way into the coffers of the European Union; their point is that the tax is required as a matter of EU law and the conditions for its application are required
default.  
defaultThe Committee is well familiar with The Sixth Directive, which goes in great detail through the things one can and cannot levy VAT on, at full rate and reduced rate and so on
default.  
defaultThe reasoning is that because the tax is required by EU law and levied within the framework of EU law, measures that member states take in order to enforce liability for that tax must be consistent with basic standards of EU procedural fairness, including the right not to be criminalised twice for the same offence
default.  
defaultMartin Howe:default I am comforted by the fact that where I am in disagreement with my colleagues on this point I am in agreement with the opinion of the German Federal 
defaultConstitutional Court
default.  
defaultIt does seem to me this is an example where a tiny or indirect connection with European Union law is being used to widen the scope of application of the Charter
default.  
defaultI do not disagree with Professor Craig’s remarks over the distinction between the scope of European Union law and actual implementation
default.  
defaultMy objection to this judgment is that I do not think this, on any reasonable basis, should be regarded as being within the scope of European Union law
default.  
defaultJust because European Union law specifies the quantum and imposes a general obligation on member states to use their general tax-raising powers to collect the money, it does not follow that the details of the mechanisms member states use to collect that and other taxes therefore fall within the scope of European law, which is what this judgment says
default.  
defaultThe observations about the interaction with national law arise directly from the excessive scope of this judgment
default.  
defaultHaving cast the net so wide, they have cast the net to cover a tax system that also involves the collection of purely national taxes
default.  
defaultThey, therefore, necessarily enmesh themselves in the problem of having two parallel sets of fundamental rights standards applying to this scenario
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ38 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Thornton:default To what extent, if at all, has the court of justice clarified the horizontal effect of the Charter, particularly in relation to rights and principles found in Title IV, in its judgment in 
defaultAssociation de 
defaultM
defaulté
defaultdiation
default 
defaultSociale
default 
defaultdelivered on 15 January
default?  
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default Those who would prefer not to see a horizontal effect of the Charter might be quite comforted by the court’s recent judgment, because they did not find a horizontal application of the Charter in that particular case
default.  
defaultThey did not find that the provision in the Charter could be used to super charge, as it were, a Directive that also covered the relevant law in that field
default.  
defaultThey found that the provision of the Charter was not sufficiently specific to give rise to a directly enforceable right that could be used in a horizontal situation between two private parties
default.  
defaultIn that respect, they did not go as far as the judgment of the Advocate General in the 
defaultAMS
default case
default, 
defaultnor did they continue down the line of some of their previous case law in 
defaultMangold
default and 
defaultKücükdeveci
default, where they seem to admit some sort of horizontal effect of general principles of law
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ39 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Thornton:default That was not able to overturn the French labour code in that case then
default?  
default&#xa0;
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default No, it was not
default.  
defaultProfessor Craig:default I agree with that
default.  
defaultI would add two things to what my colleague has said
default.  
defaultFirstly, as a matter of principle, given that the court has held, in cases such as 
defaultMangold
default and 
defaultKücükdeveci
default, 
defaultthat general principles
default of law can have a horizontal impact, it would seem to me, as a matter of principle, very odd if it held that Charter rights could never have horizontality
default.  
defaultThat does not work for me at all as a matter of first principle
default.  
defaultI am merely saying that as a matter of legal reasoning
default.  
defaultIf you have a general principle such as non-discrimination, or something of that kind, you have a Charter right covering the same terrain
default.  
defaultIf you said that a general principle, such as non-discrimination on the grounds of age, can have a horizontal impact, which is basically what they said in 
defaultKücükdeveci
default and 
defaultMangold
default, then you have an applicable or an analogous Charter right covering the same subject matter, I cannot see how you would, in principle, deny all horizontality to the latter
default.  
defaultThat is the first point
default.  
defaultThe second point that 
defaultflows from that
default is while the court held this particular Charter right, Article 27, did not qualify for horizontality for the reasons that my colleague mentioned, they also did give a hint, particularly in paragraph 47 of the judgment, that things might be different if a different Charter right had been before the court
default.  
defaultWhat they say in paragraph 47 of the judgment is that in this connection, the facts of the case may be distinguished from those that gave rise to 
defaultKücükdeveci
default,
default insofar as the principle of non-discrimination on the grounds of age, at issue in that case, laid down in Article 21(1) of the Charter is sufficient in itself to confer on individuals an individual right, which they may invoke as such
default.  
defaultIn that sense, they are excluding it in relation to Article 27 but they are not shutting the door
default.  
defaultIn fact, they are leaving the door quite wide ajar in relation to Charter rights that they think are suitable and complete, and therefore susceptible to horizontality
default.  
defaultDavid Anderson:default I agree with both my colleagues
default.  
defaultI might add one word of caution, for myself as much as anybody else: the issue of horizontality is an extraordinarily difficult one
default.  
defaultIt is not a binary issue
default.  
defaultIf you look at Charters of fundamental rights throughout the world, there is a very wide variation
default.  
defaultThe classic example of one that does not acknowledge horizontality is the Constitution of the United States and their Bill of Rights, where application is vertical only, although, even there, under the doctrine of state action, some constitutional guarantees are extended to some relationships between individuals
default.  
defaultAt the other extreme, you have Ireland, in which constitutional guarantees are given direct application in horizontal litigation between individuals
default.  
defaultA taxi driver, as I understand it, can rely on his right to earn a living in order to obtain an injunction against an unlicensed taxi driver
default.  
defaultYou might think it was horizontal litigation and all sorts of difficult situations in the middle
default.  
defaultProfessor Craig cited a very learned article on this subject, which may have been a little too much for my brain; I find Clayton and Tomlinson’s treatment of the subject in their book on human rights is a very useful introduction
default.  
defaultMartin Howe:default On this one, I agree with my colleagues’ analysis of the judgment
default.  
defaultCertainly, the court itself did not go nearly as far as was recommended by the Advocate General, who wanted to effectively create a gateway through the principle of Directives not to have horizontal effects
default.  
defaultThat does leave us, though, with the existing 
defaultKücükdeveci
default case, which is a judgment from 2010 where, although expressed in that judgment, the principle of non-discrimination on the grounds of age is based as a general principle of European Union law and as an exception to the rule against horizontal application.  The interpretation of that judgment in the 
defaultAssocia
defaultt
defaultion de 
defaultM
defaulté
defaultdiation
default 
defaultSociale
default 
defaultjudgment
default delivered last week is, in effect, to distinguish between the levels of precision of the articles of the Charter relating to these two principles
default.  
defaultTherefore, it does open the door, perhaps, to a wider rolling out of the 
defaultKücükdeveci
default principle on to other provisions of the Charter that are sufficiently precise
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ40 default&#xa0; 
defaultChris Kelly:default Can parallels be drawn between the effects of the Charter on UK courts and the effects of section 6 of the Human Rights Act, which includes courts as “public authorities”, for example in the recent decision of the employment appeal tribunal in 
defaultBenkharbouche
default?  
default&#xa0;
defaultDavid Anderson:default Yes, you can draw a parallel
default.  
defaultSection 6 of the Human Rights Act makes it plain that the courts are public authorities and are therefore bound by the requirements of the Human Rights Act
default.  
defaultThere is a vigorous academic debate, probably in fact more vigorous in its academic form than it has been so far in case law, as to exactly what that means and where 
defaultalong the almost infinite spectrum of horizontality the English courts are going to come out
default.  
defaultThe 
defaultAMS
default case is very far from the last word of the European Court of Justice on horizontality
default.  
defaultThere are bound to be many more issues to work out
default.  
defaultIn working them out, I am sure they will have regard to Article 51 of the Charter, which also addresses the obligations to bodies, including the institutions of the Union and therefore including the courts of the Union, and addresses the obligations also to the member states
default.  
defaultI would have thought—the professors may have other views—that according to the doctrine of the indivisibility of the state under international law, the reference to the member states is likely to include the courts of the member states, as well as their other institutions
default.  
defaultEven after 10 or 12 years of the Human Rights Act, we are very far from understanding exactly how its horizontal application will work out
default.  
defaultWe are further still in the case of the Charter
default.  
defaultMartin Howe:default Section 6 of the Human Rights Act is very interesting because, on the face of it, one would have thought the application of the Act to the courts is in respect of their own procedures
default.  
defaultIn other words, they are obliged to conduct their own procedures
default.  
defaultPrincipally, the requirements of Article 6 regarding fair trial are the obligations which most relevantly impact on the way courts operate
default.  
defaultWhat has happened is this has been used as an argument to introduce horizontality, most notably in the context of the creation of a new, horizontal right to privacy, which parliament itself has never decided to create through, among other things, the argument that, since the court is itself bound by Section 6 of the Human Rights Act, the court must adapt substantive doctrines of common law that apply as between citizens in order to create, in effect, new rights
default.  
defaultTherefore, the act, in effect, has binding effects on private citizens, through that gateway, as well as on public institutions
default.  
defaultCertainly, one can see a road for a parallel chained logic in the application of the EU Charter
default.  
defaultProfessor Craig:default I agree with what has already been said
default.  
defaultI would add two points
default.  
defaultFirstly, the basic problem faced in Section 6 and in Article 51, in terms of the horizontality issue, is the same
default.  
defaultIt is the point that David Anderson has already mentioned: to what extent do we think that fundamental or constitutional rights should only have a vertical application against the state, and to what extent do we believe that they should also be applicable between individuals
default?  
defaultThat issue is raised in the context of Section 6 of the HRA
default.  
defaultIt is raised in the context of Article 51 of the Charter as well
default.  
defaultI am one of those who take a rather more radical view of this kind of thing than, perhaps, some other people
default.  
defaultVery briefly, it is this: the classic argument against horizontality is that it intrudes too far into personal autonomy
default.  
defaultThat is fundamentally what it is all about: that fundamental rights should only, in principle, have an application against the state and should not have an application horizontally as between private individuals; to do so would be too intrusive on their private autonomy
default.  
defaultThe problem with that argument is that, when you start thinking about it, it looks a good deal weaker than it did at the beginning
default.  
defaultParliament and the common law are making intrusions into private autonomy the whole time
default.  
defaultThey do so with legislation the whole time
default.  
defaultThey do so with common law doctrine the whole time
default.  
defaultOne way at least—I am not saying it is the sole answer—of considering horizontality and standing back from the detail is to ask the fundamental question of principle, which is that if a right is felt to be fundamental, and hence included in a Constitutional Bill of Rights, why should it not, in principle, also be applicable as between private individuals
default?  
defaultI am not saying that there are no circumstances in which one would reach a negative answer
default.  
defaultThere may be good reasons why particular constitutional rights should not apply as between private individuals
default.  
defaultBut if you pose the question in the way I just mentioned, it is not at all obvious 
defaultthat, for example, a private individual should be able to discriminate on the grounds of sex, gender, race or anything else—even in purely private dealings with other individuals
default.  
defaultIn many instances we have statute to regulate that terrain anyway but, even if we did not, if we think as a fundamental principle those kinds of discrimination are wrong if conducted by the State, I am not quite sure why we would think they were right if conducted by private individuals
default.  
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default I would certainly agree with what Professor Craig has said, although I could add two short points
default.  
defaultOne would be that, if you look at the actual rights in the Charter, not every single one of them is capable of having horizontal effect, because some are directed only to the bodies of the Union
default.  
defaultArticle 42 on the right to access documents is one such; it is addressed only to EU agencies and institutions
default.  
defaultSecondly, I would say, as David Anderson has said, horizontality is an extremely complex subject
default.  
defaultRelated to it is the requirement that has been set down in EU law, that the courts interpret national law in the light of obligations under EU law, insofar as it is possible to do so—sometimes called indirect effect—which is often seen as an example of horizontality
default.  
defaultIt was because in the 
defaultAMS
default case that it was not possible to interpret the French measure in the light of EU law that, in fact, the Directive could not be applied
default.  
defaultBut in many cases such 
defaulta conform
default interpretation would be possible, and that would end up having a sort of horizontal effect on private parties
default.  
default 
