defaultQ42 default&#xa0; 
defaultStephen Phillips:default Now, we are all agreed that Protocol 30 is not an opt-out
default.  
defaultWe established that just before we rose for the division
default.  
defaultThat is a conclusion to which our predecessor committee came, and one of the purposes of this report is to clarify that to the house
default.  
defaultI think you also all agree, but tell me if I am wrong, that Article 1(1) of the Protocol is simply a reflection of Article 51(1) of the Charter itself
default.  
defaultIs that common ground between the four of you at least
default?  
defaultYes, I see no dissent and, indeed, lots of nodding of heads
default.  
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat I want to explore a little is to what extent you think Article 1(2) gives any additional protection for the United Kingdom against, for example, the applicability of the solidarity rights, a protection that is not contained within the Charter or within any pre-existing general principles of EU law
default.  
defaultWhat does Article 1(2) actually achieve?  Does it go beyond Article 1(1)?   
default&#xa0;
defaultProfessor Craig:default It seems to me that it does add something
default.  
defaultWhile 1(1) is certainly not an opt-out, for all the reasons we discussed last time, Article 1(2) does have the substantive content
default.  
defaultIt particularly has the substantive content in relation to those provisions of Title IV that do not have any condition about national laws and practices
default.  
defaultThe meaning of that phrase I will come back to in a moment
default.  
defaultHowever, there are certain rights or provisions within Title IV, like Article 29, concerning the right to a free placement service, and Article 31, which, in the absence of Protocol 30 Article 1(2), could or might be interpreted by the court as being genuine rights
default.  
defaultIn relation to the UK, however, Article 1(2) of Protocol 30 would prevent that interpretation from being applicable
default.  
defaultIn that respect, my view is that Article 1(2) does add a substantive impact in particular in relation to those parts of Title IV where there is no condition of the right being found in a national law or practice
default.  
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default I agree with what Professor Craig said but I would add one thing, which is that even if Article 1(2) of the Protocol does succeed in having that effect regarding certain rights, there may still be a problem with general principles of law, which might nonetheless be applicable because the Protocol does not apply to them
default.  
defaultIn that case, an interesting question would be whether rights, particularly those rights in Title IV, actually extend beyond general principles of law so that the Protocol does, as I call it in my evidence, a belt-and-braces job there
default.  
defaultOtherwise, you are still left with the problem of general principles of law taking effect
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ43 default&#xa0; 
defaultStephen Phillips:default Mr Anderson and Mr Howe, do you want to add anything to that
default?  
defaultDavid Anderson:default Not really
default.  
defaultI very much agree with Professor Craig
default.  
defaultI could quibble on one point but I do not wish to take the Committee’s time
default.  
default 
defaultStephen Phillips:default Quibble away
default.  
defaultDavid Anderson:default Perhaps implicit in what Professor Craig said was that the United Kingdom and Poland are placed in a privileged position by the Protocol; I am not sure whether he actually intended to say that or not
default.  
defaultI would see the Protocol more as confirmatory of the general position, albeit expressed to be in the context of the UK and Poland
default.  
defaultTherefore, one would expect that the added protection available in Article 1(2) ought to be available to others to argue as well
default,
default although I have not seen any sign in the case law so far of other member states taking that point
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ44 default&#xa0; 
defaultStephen Phillips:default That does rather bring me on to my next question, which is this: what on earth do the words “in particular and for the avoidance of doubt” mean at the commencement of Article 1(2) if, indeed, it contains something substantive that is not to be found in Article 1(1) of the Protocol?
default&#xa0;
defaultMartin Howe:default The only way to square the circle is by looking back to the horizontal article, Article 52, paragraph five, of the Charter, which is the one relating to the distinction between principles and rights, and to regard Article 1 paragraph 2 of the Protocol as, in effect, 
defaultclassifying everything under Title IV of the Charter as falling in the heading of principles, rather than rights
default.  
defaultIf you do that, it does not mean they have no legal effect at all, because, as we discussed at our last session, they can be relied upon to both interpret legislative acts, and thereby indirectly affect the way the law applies on the ground as it were, or indeed potentially to invalidate them, even if they are not themselves great rights of their own
default.  
defaultI strongly suspect that this will be interpreted very narrowly, because it is a very odd instrument in the sense that, on the face of it, it creates special status for Poland and the United Kingdom
default.  
defaultOn the other hand, the European Court will be very anxious to interpret it in a way that results in no special status, because they are very keen on uniform application of European Law
default.  
defaultI suspect the way they will do it is to treat it as declaratory of the underlying situation under the Charter and interpret it narrowly
default.  
defaultThe way you would interpret Article 1(2) narrowly is to focus on the word “creates”
default.  
defaultNothing in Title IV of the Charter creates 
defaultjusticiable
default rights
default.  
defaultIt does not follow that Title IV of the Charter does not alter the scope of rights that are present in other instruments
default.  
defaultDavid Anderson:default I rather agree with that
default.  
defaultFor proponents of Article 1(2) and those who want to see it given some force, it is possibly troubling that the court, so far, does not appear to have had much regard to it—perhaps because it has not been pleaded before it
default.  
defaultThe 
defaultAMS
default case was mentioned, which was decided a week ago today
default.  
defaultParagraph 45 sums up the effect of Article 27, which is one of the Title IV rights—I think the right of workers to be consulted—and the court said, “It is therefore clear from the wording of Article 27 of the Charter that for this Article to be fully effective, it must be given more specific expression in European Union or national law.”  Perhaps if the United Kingdom had been there, they would have been pushing for wording more along the lines of, “It is clear from the wording of Article 27 of the Charter, viewed in conjunction with Article 1(2) of the Protocol, that for this Article to be 
defaultjusticiable
default, it must be given specific expression in national law.”  That opportunity was not taken
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ45 default&#xa0; 
defaultStephen Phillips:default Can I move on to Article 2 of Protocol 30
default?  
defaultWhat does that achieve for the United Kingdom and for Poland, if anything
default?  
default&#xa0;
defaultProfessor Craig:default Article two is interesting
default.  
defaultIt does reveal a genuine ambiguity in the Charter
default.  
defaultWhen one looks at the particular articles in the Charter, the common phrase in relation to a number of the Charter articles in Title IV is “and under the conditions provided for by union law and national laws and practices”. 
defaultIn a literal, textual sense, the phrase “and national laws and practices” could mean one of two things
default.  
defaultIt could either mean that the particular right in question must be recognised in the national law of France, Germany or Italy, i.e
default. 
defaultwhatever State is before the court at the time
default.  
defaultThat is one view and is probably the orthodox common view
default.  
defaultIt would also be textually possible, although I am not advocating this, to read the relevant phrase, “Provided for by union law and national laws and practices,” in a broad way, to mean the following: that provided the relevant right is there in 20 of the laws of the member states, it will suffice
default.  
defaultThe way I regard Article 2 of the Protocol is for abundance of caution
default.  
defaultThat is, it is recognising that might be a possible reading of this phrase in Title IV and it is saying the UK and Poland do not buy into that broader reading
default.  
defaultAny time you mention national law and practice it has to be in the national law and practice of the UK and Poland
default.  
defaultProfessor Douglas-Scott:default When I first looked at Article 2 of the Protocol, I thought it might just be taken as confirming Article 52, paragraph 6, of the Charter, “Full account shall be taken of national laws and practices as specified in this Charter.”  However, I will add something to what Professor Craig has just said, which is with those provisions in the Charter that refer to both national and Union law, there is the risk that Union law and national law may conflict
default.  
defaultThen what should be done
default?  
defaultIn this case, Article 2 may be very useful, in that it would confirm the national law reading
default.  
defaultDavid Anderson:default I agree with Professor Craig.
defaultMartin Howe:default To illustrate this point, let us take Article 27 of the Charter, which is the worker’s right to information and consultation
default.  
defaultThat states that the workers and their representatives are guaranteed information and consultation in good time, in the cases and under the conditions provided for by Union law and national law and practices
default.  
defaultIn a sense, the right is expressed as being not a general right, but only a right that arises to the extent that either Union or national law provides it
default.  
defaultIf Union law provides a right to information or consultation, it seems to me, under general principles, that overwrites national laws and you do not need a national law basis
default.  
defaultArticle 2 of the Protocol is irrelevant to that scenario
default.  
defaultOn the face of it, Article 2 says no more than—and it is implicit in the words of Article 27—”In the cases provided for by national laws and practice.”  If there is no provision for information in a particular case under national law, then the Article 27 right is not envisaged
default.  
defaultIt might be, as Professor Craig said, to resolve an ambiguity that might have arisen looking at a survey of national laws and practices across the European Union, rather than state by state
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultQ46 default&#xa0; 
